@page
@model PrivacyModel
@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Privacy Policy";
}

<div class="privacyPage">
    <div class="privacyHero">
        <h1>@ViewData["Title"]</h1>
        <p class="privacyIntro">
            Welcome to the official privacy policy of <strong>The League of Extraordinary Coders</strong>.
            We respect your data, your clicks, and your right to browse without feeling like you have entered a suspicious side quest.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="privacyGrid">
        <section class="privacyCard">
            <h2>What We Collect</h2>
            <p>
                We may collect basic website information like page visits, clicks, and other normal activity.
                We do not collect your secret boss fight strategy, your keyboard battle cry, or your emergency snack inventory.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="privacyCard">
            <h2>How We Use It</h2>
            <p>
                We use collected information to improve the site, fix bugs, and make things work more often than they break.
                Occasionally, this also helps us identify who angered the codebase.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="privacyCard">
            <h2>Cookies</h2>
            <p>
                This site may use cookies. These are digital cookies, not edible ones, which is honestly the biggest flaw in modern computing.
                They help the site remember useful things, but they will not satisfy hunger.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="privacyCard">
            <h2>Security</h2>
            <p>
                The League of Extraordinary Coders does its best to protect your information using teamwork, logic,
                and a healthy amount of debugging. No system is perfect, but we try to keep the chaos inside the source code.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="privacyCard">
            <h2>Third-Party Services</h2>
            <p>
                Some site features may rely on outside tools or services. If they collect information,
                they do so under their own privacy rules. Every legendary league has allies, and every ally has paperwork.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="privacyCard">
            <h2>Policy Updates</h2>
            <p>
                This privacy policy may change over time as the site evolves, the features improve,
                and our variable names become slightly less embarrassing.
            </p>
        </section>
    </div>

    <div class="privacyFooterNote">
        <p>
            Questions about privacy? Contact <strong>The League of Extraordinary Coders</strong>.
            Carrier pigeons are optional, but email is faster.
        </p>
    </div>
</div>